        id: 23972,
        title: "Virgin and Child with the Young Saint John the Baptist",
        artist: "Antonio da Correggio",
        artistLife: "Italian, 1489–1534",
        date: "c. 1515",
        medium: "Oil on panel",
        dimensions: "64.2 × 50.2 cm (25 1/4 × 19 3/4 in.); Framed: 79.4 × 63.9 × 8.3 cm (31 1/4 × 25 1/8 × 3 1/4 in.)",
        imageId: "d63b9402-c42b-cce3-aa63-6d213ad621cd",
        movement: "",
        about: "Antonio da Correggio's \"Virgin and Child with the Young Saint John the Baptist\" is a delicate masterpiece that captures a tender moment of interaction between the Virgin Mary, the infant Jesus, and a young John the Baptist. Painted around 1515, this work reflects the High Renaissance's fascination with human emotion and divine grace. Correggio, known for his sophisticated use of light and shadow, created this painting during a time when religious imagery was crucial in both private devotion and public worship.\n\nThe painting showcases the Virgin holding the Christ child, while the young John the Baptist, identifiable by his iconic camel skin garment, gestures towards Jesus in a pose of reverence. This work was likely commissioned for personal devotion, reflecting the Renaissance's blending of intimate family scenes with religious significance. Correggio’s intent was to evoke not only the sacredness of these figures but also their humanity, making the divine approachable for the viewer.",
        analysis: "Correggio’s composition is both balanced and dynamic, drawing the viewer’s eye in a gentle spiral around the figures. The Virgin's relaxed posture and serene expression anchor the scene, while the Christ child engages with John, creating a subtle narrative of recognition and blessing. This triangular arrangement enhances the painting's stability and harmony.\n\nThe artist's use of color is particularly striking. The soft, warm tones of the Virgin's robes contrast with the cooler hues of the background, creating a sense of depth and highlighting the figures. Correggio’s mastery of sfumato, a technique that softens transitions between colors, is evident in the delicate rendering of flesh and fabric, lending an ethereal quality to the scene.\n\nSymbolically, the presence of John the Baptist as a child underscores the idea of predestination and the prophetic role he would play in the life of Jesus. The tender gesture of John making eye contact with Jesus hints at his future recognition of Christ's divinity. This interaction not only enriches the narrative but also invites viewers to reflect on the intertwined destinies of these figures.\n\nEmotionally, the painting radiates an atmosphere of gentle intimacy. The Virgin's maternal gaze and protective hold on Jesus convey a sense of peace and security, while the youthful curiosity of John adds an element of innocence and wonder. Correggio captures a moment of divine tranquility, inviting viewers to pause and contemplate the harmonious union of the holy family.",
        funFacts: [
            "Correggio was largely self-taught, which was rare among Renaissance artists who typically apprenticed under masters.",
            "The young John the Baptist is often depicted with a reed cross, a symbol of his future role in heralding Jesus.",
            "Correggio's works were highly influential on Baroque artists, including Peter Paul Rubens who admired his use of light.",
            "This painting is part of a smaller, more intimate scale of devotional works that were popular among Italian nobility during the Renaissance.",
            "Correggio's real name was Antonio Allegri, but he was named after his hometown, Correggio, in Northern Italy."
        ]
